  "content": {
    "problemStatement": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>3D Mensuration is the branch of mathematics that deals with the measurement of&nbsp;three-dimensional geometric shapes, including their&nbsp;surface area,&nbsp;volume,&nbsp;lateral surface area, and other related parameters. Unlike 2D shapes (flat figures), 3D objects have&nbsp;length, width, and height (or depth), making them solid structures.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><strong>&nbsp;3D Shapes: </strong></b><span>Cube, Cuboid, Sphere, Cylinder, Cone, Pyramid, Prism, etc.</span></p><h2 id=\"mensuration-terminologies\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Mensuration Terminologies</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>Here is the list of terms you will come across in mensuration class. We have provided the term, it's abbreviation, unit, and definition for easy understanding.</span></p><table><thead><tr><th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>Terms</span></th><th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>Abbreviation</span></th><th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>Unit</span></th><th style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>Definition</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Volume</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>V</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>cm</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span>&nbsp;or m</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>A 3D shape's space is referred to as its volume.</span></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Curved Surface Area</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>CSA</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>m</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>&nbsp;or cm</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>The overall area is known as a Curved surface area if there is a curved surface. Example: Sphere.</span></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Lateral Surface area</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>LSA</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>m</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>&nbsp;or cm</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>The term \"Lateral Surface area\" refers to the combined area of all lateral surfaces that encircle the provided figure.</span></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Total Surface Area</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>TSA</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>m</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>&nbsp;or cm</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>The total surface area is the total of all the curved and lateral surface areas.</span></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Square Unit</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>-</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>m</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>&nbsp;or cm</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>A square unit is the area that a square of side one unit covers.</span></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Cube Unit</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>\u2013</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>m</span><sup><span>3</span></sup><span>&nbsp;or cm</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>The space taken up by a cube with a single side.</span></td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id=\"mensuration-formula-for-3d-shapes\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Mensuration Formula for 3D Shapes</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>The following table provides a list of all mensuration formulas for 3D shapes:</span></p><table><thead></thead><tbody><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Shape</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Volume</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Curved Surface Area or Lateral Surface Area</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Total Surface Area</strong></b></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><b><strong>Figure</strong></b></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude-cube\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Cube</strong></b></a></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>a</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>LSA = 4 a</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>6a</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-11-100.webp\" alt=\"Shapes-11\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-11.webp 250w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-11-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-11-200.webp 200w\"><figcaption>cube dimensions</figcaption></figure></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude-cuboid-shape-and-properties\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Cuboids</strong></b></a></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>l \u00d7 b \u00d7 h</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>LSA = 2h(l + b)</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2(lb +bh +hl)</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-12-100.webp\" alt=\"Shapes-12\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-12.webp 250w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-12-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010323/Shapes-12-200.webp 200w\" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>cuboid dimensions</figcaption></figure></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude-sphere\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Sphere</strong></b></a></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>(4/3)\u03c0r</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>4\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>4\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010324/Shapes-13-100.webp\" alt=\"Shapes-13\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010324/Shapes-13.webp 250w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010324/Shapes-13-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010324/Shapes-13-200.webp 200w\" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>sphere dimensions</figcaption></figure></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude-hemisphere\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><strong>Hemisphere</strong></b></a></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>(\u2154)\u03c0r</span><sup><span>3</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>3\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-14-100.webp\" alt=\"Shapes-14\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-14.webp 250w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-14-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-14-200.webp 200w\" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>hemisphere dimensions</figcaption></figure></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude-cylinder\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\"><b><strong>Cylinder</strong></b></a></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>h</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2\u03c0rh</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>2\u03c0rh + 2\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-15-100.webp\" alt=\"Shapes-15\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-15.webp 250w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-15-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010321/Shapes-15-200.webp 200w\" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>cylinder dimensions</figcaption></figure></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"#/articles/course/AptitudeCourses/gfg-sub-aptitude-cone\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\"><b><strong>Cone</strong></b></a></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>(\u2153)\u03c0r</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>h</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>\u03c0rl</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><span>\u03c0r(r + l)</span></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010322/Shapes-16-100.webp\" alt=\"Shapes-16\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010322/Shapes-16.webp 250w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010322/Shapes-16-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20230508010322/Shapes-16-200.webp 200w\" loading=\"lazy\"><figcaption>cone dimensions</figcaption></figure></td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id=\"mensuration-3d-questions-and-answers\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Mensuration 3D - Questions and Answers</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><strong>Q1</strong></b><span>: Find the length of the largest rod that can be kept in a cuboidal room of dimensions 10 x 15 x 6 m.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution </strong></b><span>:&nbsp;</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Largest rod would lie along the diagonal.&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Length of largest rod = Length of diagonal of the room = (L</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">2</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> + B</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">2 </em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">+ H</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">2</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">)1/2&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Length of the largest rod = (102 + 152 + 62)1/2 = (100 + 225 + 36)1/2 = (361)1/2&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Length of the largest rod = 19 m&nbsp;</em></i></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><strong>Q2</strong></b><span>: Find the number of bricks of dimension 24 x 12 x 8 cm each that would be required to make a wall 24 m long, 8 m high and 60 cm thick.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution </strong></b><span>:&nbsp;</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Volume of 1 brick = 24 x 12 x 8 = 2304 cm </em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Volume of wall = 2400 x 800 x 60 = 115200000 cm</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> 3&nbsp;</em></sup></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Therefore, number of bricks required = 115200000 / 2304 = 50000</em></i></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><strong>Q3</strong></b><span>: A rectangular sheet of paper measuring 22 cm x 7 cm is rolled along the longer side to make a cylinder. Find the volume of the cylinder formed.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution</strong></b><span>:&nbsp;</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Let the radius of the cylinder be \u2018R\u2019.&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">The sheet is rolled along the longer side.&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; 2 \u03c0 R = 22&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; R = 3.5 cm&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Also, height = 7 cm&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Therefore, volume of the cylinder = \u03c0 R2 H = \u03c0 (3.5)2 7 = 269.5 cm</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">&nbsp;</em></i></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><strong>Q4</strong></b><span>: If each edge of a cube is increased by 10 %, what would be the percentage increase in volume?&nbsp;</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution</strong></b><span>:&nbsp;</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Let the original edge length be \u2018a\u2019&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Original volume = a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3&nbsp;</em></sup></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Now, new edge length = 1.1 a&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; New volume = (1.1 a)</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3 </em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">= 1.331 a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3&nbsp;</em></sup></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Increase in volume = 1.331 a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> \u2013 1 a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> = 0.331 a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3&nbsp;</em></sup></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Therefore, percentage increase in volume = (0.331 a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> / a</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3)</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> x 100 = 33.1 %&nbsp;</em></i></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><b><strong>Q5</strong></b><span>: Three metal cubes of edge lengths 3 cm, 4 cm, and 5 cm are melted to form a single cube. Find the edge length of such a cube.&nbsp;</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Solution</strong></b><span>:&nbsp;</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">Volume of new cube = Volume of metal generated on melting the cubes = Sum of volumes of the three cubes&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Volume of new cube = 3 </em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> + 4 </em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3 </em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">+ 5 </em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> = 216&nbsp;</em></i><br><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">=&gt; Edge length of new cube = (216)</em></i><i><sup><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\">1/3</em></sup></i><i><em class=\"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic\"> = 6 cm&nbsp;</em></i></p></blockquote>",
    "sampleTestCases": []
  }
}